  "slug": "krupnik",
  "title": "Krupnik",
  "subtitle": "Polish barley and vegetable soup",
  "excerpt": "Pearl barley simmered in a rich chicken broth with root vegetables, dried porcini, and dill. The most comforting of the Polish everyday soups, thick, earthy, and made better the next day.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Krupnik (from the Polish word krupa, meaning groats or grain) is one of the oldest soups in Polish cookery, mentioned in historical records from the sixteenth century. Pearl barley and root vegetables cooked in bone broth formed part of the everyday diet across Poland, Belarus, and Ukraine. The addition of dried mushrooms is a Polish feature found in many regional versions.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Krupnik is a thick barley soup that sits between a broth and a stew. The pearl barley swells as it cooks and releases starch into the liquid, giving the finished soup a body that is impossible to achieve with any other grain. It is the soup that Polish families make when someone needs feeding up, when the weather turns, or when there is a leftover chicken carcass in the refrigerator.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Dried porcini add a depth that lifts the broth considerably. Soak them for 30 minutes, then add both the mushrooms and the strained soaking liquid to the pot. They are not essential, but the soup is noticeably better with them.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
